  Key Points to Say in Interview
                                
  ▎ "I distinguish between RequestType and Direction because hall calls are never IDLE — using Direction would require runtime validation that the type system should prevent. Request is a frozen dataclass so 
  it's hashable and safe in a set, which gives O(1) deduplication.                                                                                                                                              
  
  ▎ step() has five cases in order: empty → go IDLE; IDLE with requests → pick direction deterministically; at a stop → remove and don't move this tick; no requests ahead → reverse and don't move this tick;  
  otherwise → move. The order matters: you must pick direction before checking for stops, and you must check for stops before reversing.
                                                                                                                                                                                                                
  ▎ _has_requests_ahead checks ALL request types regardless of direction — the elevator travels toward everything but only stops for matching types. An elevator going UP passes a PICKUP_DOWN floor and serves 
  it on the return trip. This is correct SCAN behavior, not a bug.
                                                                                                                                                                                                                
  ▎ The controller's lock serializes select + add atomically — without it, two concurrent hall calls could both pick the same elevator as 'best' and create race conditions on the set."                        
  
